{
  "doc_id": "4807",
  "text": "However, in later pregnancy, endoscopic derotation could be limited by enlargement of the uterus [CITATION_1] , and surgical derotation or sigmoidectomy are often chosen as treatment: resection could be eventually postponed in the post-partum in cases of viable tissue [CITATION_2] , whereas the presence of non-viable tissue requires bowel resection with a diverting colostomy. Primary anastomosis of edematous large bowel is avoided because it could be hazardous to both mother and foetus [CITATION_3] .",
